body:
Ok. The conflict is between PcxDecode.c:62, which deals in a buffer size of stride*bands, and Unpack.c:403, which deals in pixel width. It's assigning `out[G] = in[i+pixels] which is an off by one, since that's going to be in the padding.   (This still doesn't explain why the blue is still only off by one. It should be off by two). 

I think what should happen is something like this just before PcxDecode.c:62:

```
if (state->bytes % state->xsize && state->butes >  state->xsize) {
   int bands = state->bytes / state->xsize;
   int stride = state->bytes / bands;
   for (int i=1; i< bands; i++) {  // note -- skipping first band
      memmove(&state->buffer[i*state->xsize], &state->buffer[i*stride], state->xsize);
   }
}
```

Try https://github.com/wiredfool/Pillow/commit/5ecec7db105ba48b20b1d6b8496d7caf49759243 and see if it does it for you. 

If that works, then we just need to find a redistributable test image that works (though I'd bet we could write one easily enough) and include that in the test suite.  Imagemagick isn't doing even-only strides, helpfully enough.
